[[File:Doinel, Jules.jpg|right|thumb|<center>Jules Doinel]] {{gnosticism}} '''Jules-Benoît Stanislas Doinel du Val-Michel''' (December 8, 1842, [[Moulins, Allier]] &ndash; March 16 or 17, 1903), also simply '''Jules Doinel''', was an archivist and the founder of the first [[Gnosticism in modern times|Gnostic church]] in modern times.
==Gnostic Church Revival==
After spiritual experiences in 1888-89, he proclaimed 1890 the beginning of "the era of Gnosis restored." Doinel assumed the office of Patriarch of the ''[[Église Gnostique]]'' ([[French Language|French]]: ''Gnostic Church''), taking the ecclesiastical name of '''Tau Valentin II''', after [[Valentinius]], the 2nd century Christian Gnostic teacher.<ref>[[#refPearsWiccal|Pearson, J. (2007) p. 46]]</ref> <ref>[[#refWaiteDevil|Waite (1896) p. 185]]</ref>
The doctrinal orientation of the church was based on extant Cathar documents, with the Gospel of John, and strong influence of [[Simon Magus|Simonian]] and [[Valentinus (Gnostic)|Valentinian]] [[cosmology]], the church was officially established in the [[autumn]] of 1890 in [[Paris (France)|Paris, France]]. Liturgical services were based on Cathar rituals. Clergy were both male and female, having male bishops and female "sophias."<ref>[[#refHoellGnos|Hoeller (2002) p. 176-8]]</ref>
Doinel was "spiritually consecrated" in a spiritual experience in 1888 and not into a line of [[apostolic succession]]. Doinel subsequently consecrated a number of bishops for the ''Église Gnostique'', notable among these was [[Gérard Encausse]] founder of the closely allied [[Martinist Order]].<ref>[[#refPearsWiccal|Pearson, J. (2007) p. 47]]</ref><ref>[[#refHoellGnos|Hoeller (2002) p. 177]]</ref>
==Anti-Masonic Period (1895-1897)==
In 1895, Doinel resigned from the ''Église Gnostique'', leaving the leadership of the church to a council of bishops. Doinel then converted to [[Roman Catholicism]] and began a collaboration with [[Léo Taxil]], one of many taken in by Taxil's [[Taxil hoax|anti-masonic hoax]]. Doinel wrote a book entitled ''Lucifer Unmasked'', a book attacking freemasonry, under the name '''Jean Kostka''', in which he associated many of his prior activities with the diabolic. [[A. E. Waite]] described ''Lucifer Unmasked'' and revealed the real identity of its author in ''Devil Worship in France'' his exposé of the anti-masonic movement Taxil inspired.<ref>[[#refWaiteDevil|Waite (1896) p. 184]]</ref> Taxil unveiled his hoax in 1897.
==Reconciliation==
Doinel was readmitted as a bishop in the ''Église Gnostique'' in 1900.
